13:45.158 --> 13:55.168
**

13:55.202 --> 14:02.609
**

14:02.642 --> 14:04.211
Okay, well, why the bottle?

14:04.244 --> 14:06.246
The air will continue
to leak and accumulate

14:06.279 --> 14:08.348
until the damage
can be properly repaired.

14:08.381 --> 14:09.549
The tube allows
the air to get out.

14:09.582 --> 14:12.185
The water in the bottle stops
the air from coming back in.

14:12.219 --> 14:14.221
A homemade one-way valve.

14:14.254 --> 14:16.323
[ Gasps ]

14:16.356 --> 14:18.125
He's breathing.

14:18.158 --> 14:19.960
[ Cries ]

14:19.993 --> 14:22.429
You saved his life.

14:22.462 --> 14:24.264
He saved his life!

14:24.297 --> 14:26.366
[ Applause ]

14:26.399 --> 14:33.573
**

14:37.577 --> 14:39.246
Woman: 235 to Seattle,
now departing from Gate B42.

14:39.279 --> 14:42.182
Shaun, where are you? I-I --

14:42.215 --> 14:43.383
-[ Clears throat ]
-Call me as soon

14:43.416 --> 14:44.484
as you can, please.

14:44.517 --> 14:46.119
That was a mistake.
I agree,

14:46.153 --> 14:48.155
'cause it's not about the new
doctor, this is about you.

14:48.188 --> 14:50.057
They're baiting you.
And you're letting them.

14:50.090 --> 14:51.191
Maybe.
Maybe what?

14:51.224 --> 14:52.559
What mistake
are you talking about?

14:52.592 --> 14:54.027
Your shot
at Andrews' nephew.

14:54.061 --> 14:55.963
Oh, come on.
It was funny.

14:55.996 --> 14:58.231
It was very funny.
It was also disrespectful.

14:58.265 --> 14:59.166
Well, you don't
show him respect.

14:59.199 --> 15:01.234
I assume it's because
you don't respect him.

15:01.268 --> 15:03.103
You show someone respect
because you respect them,

15:03.136 --> 15:04.237
or because you're
afraid of them.

15:04.271 --> 15:05.705
I don't fit into
either category.

15:05.738 --> 15:07.174
Well, neither do I.

15:07.207 --> 15:09.242
You should.

15:09.276 --> 15:11.979
You're only in that room
because your grandfather

15:12.012 --> 15:15.515
founded this hospital.

15:15.548 --> 15:17.250
I'm gonna pretend
that this conversation

15:17.284 --> 15:19.352
didn't take this tangent,
and instead focus on something

15:19.386 --> 15:22.222
relevant -- the debate
you are losing.

15:22.255 --> 15:23.390
Here's how you win this.

15:23.423 --> 15:26.393
You don't make it personal.
You do not make it about you.

15:26.426 --> 15:28.962
That is what they want,
and if you give it to them,

15:28.996 --> 15:32.065
you will lose.

15:32.099 --> 15:34.101
[ Siren wails ]

15:34.134 --> 15:37.504
I need to get to San Jose
St. Bonaventure Hospital.

15:37.537 --> 15:38.671
That's where
we're going.

15:38.705 --> 15:40.307
Good.

15:40.340 --> 15:42.609
[ Monitor beeping ]

15:42.642 --> 15:46.713
**

15:46.746 --> 15:48.215
Ethan: How hard can it be

15:48.248 --> 15:50.483
to just act like
a normal human being?!

15:50.517 --> 15:52.685
-He doesn't know how.
-Bull!

15:52.719 --> 15:54.654
What are we supposed
to do now? Huh?

15:54.687 --> 15:56.756
This is the third school
he's been thrown out of.

15:56.789 --> 15:57.690
We'll find another school.

15:57.724 --> 15:59.692
No, we won't, 'cause
nothing's gonna change.

15:59.726 --> 16:02.029
They can't handle him,
and I don't blame them,

16:02.062 --> 16:03.630
'cause obviously,
we can't handle him, either.

16:03.663 --> 16:05.165
What the hell
happened this time?

16:05.198 --> 16:06.699
What happened?!

16:06.733 --> 16:07.767
You're hurting him.

16:07.800 --> 16:10.503
[ Grunting ]

16:10.537 --> 16:12.105
What did you do?!

16:12.139 --> 16:14.074
Shaun!
No!

16:14.107 --> 16:16.109
Will you stop petting
that stupid rabbit?!

16:16.143 --> 16:18.745
[ Thud ]

16:18.778 --> 16:28.755
**

16:28.788 --> 16:31.324
It changed.

16:31.358 --> 16:34.561
The boy's ECG changed.

16:34.594 --> 16:37.164
It's the same --
86 BPM.

16:37.197 --> 16:39.366
No. It used
to be higher.

16:39.399 --> 16:41.734
No, it used to be 86.
It's still 86.

16:41.768 --> 16:44.804
It used to come up to here.

16:44.837 --> 16:46.706
Lower amplitude
means lower voltage.

16:46.739 --> 16:49.076
Lower amplitude
means lower voltage.

16:49.109 --> 16:50.543
What's going on?
What does it mean?

16:50.577 --> 16:52.545
It means he's trying to read
20-year-old equipment

16:52.579 --> 16:54.781
while traveling in a vehicle
going 40 miles an hour.

16:54.814 --> 16:56.616
[ Beeping ]

16:56.649 --> 16:57.784
How did you get him
to sign?

16:57.817 --> 17:00.453
I simply told him it was either
consenting or going home,

17:00.487 --> 17:05.225
then I gave him two forms
and told him to pick one.

17:05.258 --> 17:07.127
Melendez: And you highlighted
the Release Against

17:07.160 --> 17:08.495
Medical Advice form
that mentions

17:08.528 --> 17:11.764
the "possibility of death
or permanent disability"?

17:11.798 --> 17:13.100
Well done.

17:13.133 --> 17:14.701
Hand me the Metz and a pick-up.

17:14.734 --> 17:16.269
I'm isolating
the descending aorta.

17:16.303 --> 17:19.339
Sarah:
Vascular clamp.

17:19.372 --> 17:20.773
What is that?

17:20.807 --> 17:22.375
Under the left atrium...

17:22.409 --> 17:24.844
something white.

17:24.877 --> 17:27.647
Is that part of the lung?

17:27.680 --> 17:30.350
Melendez: It's pus.

17:30.383 --> 17:31.484
Did he have TB?

17:31.518 --> 17:32.419
No, he doesn't have any--

17:32.452 --> 17:33.786
No, not currently.
Does he have a history--

17:33.820 --> 17:35.122
When he was younger,
he was exposed to --

17:35.155 --> 17:36.256
This is an abscess.
It's gonna bur--

17:36.289 --> 17:38.091
[ Monitor beeping rapidly ]
[ Gasps ]

17:38.125 --> 17:40.427
Suction and a lap sponge.
His BP's crashing.

17:40.460 --> 17:41.794
Two liters saline
wide open.

17:41.828 --> 17:44.597
Set up the level one.
Two units packed cells now.

17:44.631 --> 17:47.334
Get Levophed on board
and keep that MAP at 60.

17:47.367 --> 17:49.369
Get in there with the suction.
I can't see a damn thing.

17:49.402 --> 17:51.571
Suction.

17:51.604 --> 17:53.240
I hope it isn't too upsetting
to him when he hears

17:53.273 --> 17:54.541
he would have
died in his room

17:54.574 --> 17:56.343
if we'd waited
until tomorrow.

17:56.376 --> 17:58.811
Dr. Melendez, we've got
an incoming 8-year-old male,

17:58.845 --> 18:00.280
pneumothorax stabilized,

18:00.313 --> 18:02.115
but undetermined
internal injuries.

18:02.149 --> 18:03.283
Who do you want to catch?

18:03.316 --> 18:05.252
Claire, I don't
think we need you.

18:05.285 --> 18:08.521
This patient
is gonna be fine...now.

18:11.258 --> 18:12.325
8-year-old healthy boy,

18:12.359 --> 18:14.327
status post encounter with
a shattered glass sign.

18:14.361 --> 18:15.495
Numerous lacerations.

18:15.528 --> 18:17.564
-Echo --
-Get him set up in Trauma 3

18:17.597 --> 18:19.832
with an EKG, full
blood work and a pan-scan.

18:19.866 --> 18:21.868
We need
an echo-- echocardiogram.

18:21.901 --> 18:22.769
Who is this guy?

18:22.802 --> 18:24.571
He helped with first-aid
at the airport.

18:24.604 --> 18:26.806
I'm the doctor.
He needs an echocardiogram.

18:26.839 --> 18:28.341
Where are you taking him?
To surgery.

18:28.375 --> 18:30.477
All cardiac vital signs
are within normal range.

18:30.510 --> 18:31.344
Do you have any I.D.?

18:31.378 --> 18:33.546
No. His -- His heart.
It's his heart.

18:33.580 --> 18:35.548
His heart is fine.
Now stay here.

18:35.582 --> 18:37.317
Adam needs
an echocardiogram.

18:37.350 --> 18:40.487
No. Behave yourself. Or you'll
be removed from the building.

18:40.520 --> 18:45.525
**

18:45.558 --> 18:48.328
[ Grunts ]

18:48.361 --> 18:52.299
[ Breathing heavily ]

18:52.332 --> 18:53.900
Echo. Echo.

19:00.973 --> 19:02.542
Melendez: What's that?

19:02.575 --> 19:03.776
Claire: A one-way valve.

19:03.810 --> 19:08.281
And he reports the boy
suffered a pneumothorax.

19:08.315 --> 19:10.550
That is cool.

19:10.583 --> 19:16.789
**

19:16.823 --> 19:19.392
Do you think we should
do an echocardiogram?

19:19.426 --> 19:21.261
Based on the presenting
symptoms, which give

19:21.294 --> 19:23.763
no indication that
an echocardiogram is necessary,

19:23.796 --> 19:26.599
I'm going to answer no.

19:26.633 --> 19:27.900
Am I missing something?

19:27.934 --> 19:29.969
No, sir.

19:30.002 --> 19:31.404
Knife.

19:31.438 --> 19:41.414
**

19:41.448 --> 19:51.424
**

19:51.458 --> 20:01.434
**

20:01.468 --> 20:11.444
**

20:11.478 --> 20:20.420
**

20:20.453 --> 20:23.623
Glassman : We don't normally
treat rabbits, especially --

20:23.656 --> 20:25.992
This was the closest doctor
place, and it was an emergency.

20:26.025 --> 20:26.993
No, I can see that.

20:27.026 --> 20:32.499
But even if I was a vet,
the rabbit...is dead.

20:32.532 --> 20:34.701
[ Cries softly ]

20:34.734 --> 20:37.737
I'm sorry, guys.

20:37.770 --> 20:42.275
Everything smells
different when it rains.

20:42.309 --> 20:45.044
What do we do now?

20:45.077 --> 20:49.015
Well, you should
bury him, I guess.

20:49.048 --> 20:51.951
I don't know, give him
a -- a nice funeral.

20:51.984 --> 20:54.887
Has he gone to heaven?

20:58.658 --> 21:01.294
Yeah, sure. Uh, sure --
sure, he has. Um...

21:01.328 --> 21:04.531
No, I don't want him to go to
heaven! I want him to be here!

21:04.564 --> 21:07.867
[ Sobs ]

21:07.900 --> 21:09.068
This won't happen again.

21:09.101 --> 21:11.571
It can't happen again.
He's dead.

21:11.604 --> 21:12.772
I know that.

21:12.805 --> 21:15.375
I mean, nothing like this
is ever going to happen to us,

21:15.408 --> 21:16.676
ever again.

21:16.709 --> 21:19.546
Because we're not
going home.

21:19.579 --> 21:21.981
We're never
going home again.

21:22.014 --> 21:24.417
We have each other,
and that's all we need.

21:24.451 --> 21:33.893
**

21:33.926 --> 21:36.463
Andrews: A surgeon needs
to communicate --

21:36.496 --> 21:41.768
not just information,
but sympathy, empathy.

21:41.801 --> 21:43.870
Can Dr. Murphy do that?

21:43.903 --> 21:47.940
He can't even reliably show up
for a job interview.

21:47.974 --> 21:49.809
Are you gonna sit here
and tell us that there were

21:49.842 --> 21:55.081
no other equally-qualified
young surgeons --

21:55.114 --> 21:59.118
surgeons without this
one's...issues?

21:59.151 --> 22:00.252
No.

22:00.286 --> 22:04.424
Which is why -- exactly why --
we should hire Shaun.

22:04.457 --> 22:06.926
We should hire him
because he is qualified

22:06.959 --> 22:09.095
and because
he is different.

22:09.128 --> 22:10.897
How long ago was it
that we wouldn't hire

22:10.930 --> 22:12.832
black doctors
in this hospital?

22:12.865 --> 22:14.867
How m-- How long ago was it
that we wouldn't hire

22:14.901 --> 22:17.737
female doctors
at this hospital?

22:17.770 --> 22:20.640
So, you're comparing
being African-American

22:20.673 --> 22:23.042
or a woman
with being autistic.

22:23.075 --> 22:25.077
Please, go on...

22:25.111 --> 22:29.115
Okay. [ Chuckles ]

22:29.148 --> 22:32.419
The rationalization
is exactly the same.

22:32.452 --> 22:35.988
Words like "temperament"
and, "Oh, no! Ohh!

22:36.022 --> 22:38.024
How are the patients
going to react?"

22:38.057 --> 22:40.159
Aren't we judged
by how we treat people?

22:40.192 --> 22:43.696
I don't mean as doctors.
I mean as people.

22:43.730 --> 22:45.432
Especially those who --
who don't have

22:45.465 --> 22:47.500
the same advantages
that we have.

22:47.534 --> 22:50.470
We hire Shaun,
and we give hope to those people

22:50.503 --> 22:52.138
with limitations
that those limitations

22:52.171 --> 22:54.607
are not what
they think they are,

22:54.641 --> 22:57.744
that they do have a shot!

22:59.946 --> 23:02.048
[ Sighs ]

23:02.081 --> 23:06.986
We hire Shaun, and we make this
hospital better for it.

23:07.019 --> 23:11.458
We hire Shaun, and we are
better people for it.

23:11.491 --> 23:14.994
We'd be "better people,"

23:15.027 --> 23:19.866
spending a lot more on
malpractice insurance.

23:19.899 --> 23:22.802
-How old is this kid again?
-8.

23:22.835 --> 23:25.104
Spong stick.

23:25.137 --> 23:27.707
[ Monitor beeping ]

23:30.977 --> 23:32.912
What was his heart rate
five minutes ago?

23:32.945 --> 23:34.146
Uh, 86.

23:34.180 --> 23:35.114
You sure?

23:35.147 --> 23:38.150
Certain. He's been a rock.
It's barely changed.

23:38.184 --> 23:41.554
No, something's changed.
Something's different.

23:45.625 --> 23:46.959
You asked earlier about an echo.

23:46.993 --> 23:49.929
You had no medical reason,
but you asked anyway. Why?

23:49.962 --> 23:52.098
There was this weird guy,
the one that did

23:52.131 --> 23:54.033
the one-way valve,
he kept insisting

23:54.066 --> 23:56.002
that the boy needed
an echocardiogram.

23:56.035 --> 23:57.203
He didn't say why?

23:57.236 --> 23:59.572
H-He was really weird.

23:59.606 --> 24:01.007
[ Monitor beeping rapidly ]

24:01.040 --> 24:03.242
His blood pressure's dropping.
That makes no sense.

24:03.275 --> 24:06.879
He's not bleeding anymore.
Everything's under control.

24:06.913 --> 24:08.214
Do an echo.

24:08.247 --> 24:10.249
Sir, the boy is wide open.
It's gonna take awhile.

24:10.282 --> 24:11.884
Good. That'll give me
time to figure out

24:11.918 --> 24:13.486
why the hell
we're doing an echo.

24:13.520 --> 24:14.353
Dr. Browne, you're with me.

24:14.386 --> 24:15.755
We're gonna go find
your weird guy.

24:15.788 --> 24:18.591
Keep him stable.

24:20.660 --> 24:22.762
Why the echo?

24:22.795 --> 24:26.933
Uh, okay.
He, uh -- He -- Okay.

24:26.966 --> 24:30.503
Uh, he --
Uh, I, uh -- He --

24:30.537 --> 24:34.206
Okay. I understand you think
he needs an echocardiogram.

24:34.240 --> 24:36.776
We just don't know why.

24:36.809 --> 24:39.612
Well, I-I noticed that
there was a slight reduction

24:39.646 --> 24:41.681
in the intensity
of the electrocardiogram.

24:41.714 --> 24:43.716
The electrical flow --
I noticed that, too.

24:43.750 --> 24:46.586
The heart rate was the same,
but the amplitude dropped.

24:46.619 --> 24:47.920
Pericardial effusion.

24:47.954 --> 24:49.255
Reduced cardiac output.

24:49.288 --> 24:50.890
Would stress other organs.

24:50.923 --> 24:52.158
Causing them to shut down.

24:52.191 --> 24:53.826
Yes.

24:53.860 --> 24:55.728
[ Cellphone rings ]

24:55.762 --> 24:57.096
Hold on.

24:57.129 --> 24:59.265
Yeah, we're coming
right back up --

24:59.298 --> 25:01.668
Thank you.

25:01.701 --> 25:03.870
They did the echo.
It's normal.

25:03.903 --> 25:05.071
No pericardial effusion.

25:05.104 --> 25:08.007
No. It has to be. There --
There is no other explanation.

25:08.040 --> 25:11.811
The echo is normal, which
means we just wasted our time.

25:11.844 --> 25:14.581
N-No.

25:14.614 --> 25:21.754
**

25:21.788 --> 25:24.090
[ Mumbling indistinctly ]

25:24.123 --> 25:27.026
Okay, um, hey,
come with me.

25:27.059 --> 25:30.563
Come on.

25:34.133 --> 25:42.308
**

25:42.341 --> 25:44.744
Show them.

25:44.777 --> 25:52.952
**

25:52.985 --> 25:54.787
Again.

25:54.821 --> 25:58.891
**

25:58.925 --> 26:01.360
Again.

26:01.393 --> 26:03.963
Again.

26:03.996 --> 26:05.197
There.

26:05.231 --> 26:07.166
Looks normal to me.

26:07.199 --> 26:08.801
[ Chuckles ]
It's not normal.

26:08.835 --> 26:11.170
There's a concave deformity
in the right atrium.

26:11.203 --> 26:13.005
Um, no, there's not.

26:13.039 --> 26:15.307
Yeah. Yes, there is.
It's very subtle.

26:15.341 --> 26:16.375
Even if you are right,

26:16.408 --> 26:19.612
that's not where a pericardial
effusion manifests.

26:21.948 --> 26:24.751
Not usually.

26:24.784 --> 26:28.187
But it -- it could.

26:28.220 --> 26:32.124
This kid was sprayed with glass
shards -- cut his jugular.

26:32.158 --> 26:35.161
What if a piece of glass
entered his blood stream?

26:35.194 --> 26:37.764
It could have traveled
down the jugular vein,

26:37.797 --> 26:39.632
into the brachiocephalic vein

26:39.666 --> 26:41.233
and on to
the superior vena cava.

26:41.267 --> 26:43.936
If it punctured the SVC,
blood could be leaking

26:43.970 --> 26:45.772
behind the heart,
restricting the heart's ability

26:45.805 --> 26:47.874
to expand and fill
during diastole,

26:47.907 --> 26:49.241
reducing the heart's efficiency.

26:49.275 --> 26:52.378
[ Smacks lips ]
Lot of ifs there.

26:52.411 --> 26:56.916
**

26:56.949 --> 27:01.187
Dr. Chen, pair of 14-gauge
on a syringe.

27:01.220 --> 27:05.191
**

27:05.224 --> 27:08.360
All in favor of ratifying
Dr. Glassman's decision

27:08.394 --> 27:10.897
in hiring Dr. Shaun Murphy?

27:15.034 --> 27:17.303
All against.

27:20.206 --> 27:21.273
[ Knocks ]
Excuse me.

27:21.307 --> 27:22.742
Is this a medical emergency?

27:22.775 --> 27:23.843
No. No medical
emergency --

27:23.876 --> 27:25.044
Then you weren't
supposed to interrupt --

27:25.077 --> 27:27.313
Yes, I know, but you
need to go online.

27:27.346 --> 27:29.181
-What? What site?
-Pretty much any of them --

27:29.215 --> 27:32.184
Twitter, YouTube,
any local news site.

27:32.218 --> 27:37.223
**

27:37.256 --> 27:39.058
He saved his life!

27:39.091 --> 27:43.062
[ Applause ]

27:43.095 --> 27:45.798
The YouTube clip already has
over 200,000 views.

27:45.832 --> 27:49.235
Apparently, he's one
of our doctors.

27:49.268 --> 27:53.039
Dr. Shaun Murphy
saved this boy?

27:53.072 --> 27:55.407
The boy is in O.R. 2.

27:55.441 --> 27:59.111
Dr. Melendez isn't sure
if he's going to make it.

27:59.145 --> 28:08.287
**

28:08.320 --> 28:13.092
Your fiancÃ© sure can
handle a knife.

28:13.125 --> 28:15.795
Why did you warn me about
respecting Dr. Andrews?

28:15.828 --> 28:17.396
[ Smacks lips ]

28:19.932 --> 28:21.167
What's going on?

28:21.200 --> 28:23.936
I'm not gonna always
be here to protect you.

28:23.970 --> 28:27.173
You think
you're gonna lose?

28:27.206 --> 28:29.375
Everybody loses...

28:29.408 --> 28:31.710
eventually.

28:34.080 --> 28:36.315
Is that your guy?

28:36.348 --> 28:44.290
**

28:44.323 --> 28:52.231
**

28:52.264 --> 28:54.233
Can we get a TV?

28:54.266 --> 28:55.467
No.

28:55.501 --> 28:58.104
Why not?

28:58.137 --> 29:00.072
Because we're poor, dude.

29:00.106 --> 29:03.075
We live in a bus.

29:03.109 --> 29:06.245
Do you think Mom
is looking for us?

29:06.278 --> 29:08.347
Nope.

29:11.417 --> 29:17.323
She loves us, but she knows
it's better this way.

29:17.356 --> 29:27.166
**

29:27.199 --> 29:29.101
I got you a present.

29:29.135 --> 29:30.937
It's not my birthday.

29:30.970 --> 29:34.306
I got you a present anyway.

29:34.340 --> 29:42.281
**

29:42.314 --> 29:50.289
**

29:50.322 --> 29:52.258
Here.

29:52.291 --> 29:55.895
**

29:55.928 --> 29:58.530
[ Clattering ]

29:58.564 --> 30:07.506
**

30:07.539 --> 30:16.515
**

30:16.548 --> 30:25.524
**

30:25.557 --> 30:34.533
**

30:34.566 --> 30:37.103
Kelly.

30:37.136 --> 30:47.113
**

30:47.146 --> 30:52.451
**

30:52.484 --> 30:57.990
Dr. Browne...

30:58.024 --> 31:01.193
You were right.

31:01.227 --> 31:03.595
[ Chuckles softly ]

31:03.629 --> 31:09.101
**

31:09.135 --> 31:14.440
**

31:18.677 --> 31:20.646
I don't like pickles.
I know.

31:20.679 --> 31:23.582
I don't want pickles.
And I checked.

31:25.684 --> 31:28.454
You saved
that boy's life.

31:28.487 --> 31:29.922
Oh, good.

31:29.956 --> 31:31.924
His name is Adam.

31:31.958 --> 31:34.460
Traumatic pneumothorax.

31:34.493 --> 31:36.996
I'm hungry.

31:39.966 --> 31:43.102
Board reconvenes
in 45 minutes.

31:46.505 --> 31:50.409
Can you stay here
until I get back?

31:50.442 --> 31:54.213
Okay.

31:54.246 --> 31:55.381
Okay.

31:55.414 --> 31:57.216
[ Clears throat ]

32:03.122 --> 32:05.091
He's got
a serious deficit.

32:05.124 --> 32:07.193
A child is alive today
because of that deficit.

32:07.226 --> 32:09.195
And tomorrow, one may
be dead because of it.

32:09.228 --> 32:11.230
I seem to remember that
when I hired you,

32:11.263 --> 32:15.367
you weren't exactly making
the most adult decisions.

32:15.401 --> 32:17.636
You haven't killed
anyone yet. Have you?

32:17.669 --> 32:20.139
Well, thankfully,
there's a cure for youth

32:20.172 --> 32:22.408
and stupidity --
time and experience.

32:22.441 --> 32:24.476
[ Laughs ] There's
a cure for stupidity?

32:24.510 --> 32:25.978
Okay.

32:26.012 --> 32:27.980
That would be a windfall.

32:28.014 --> 32:31.683
All Shaun has is a diagnosis.

32:31.717 --> 32:33.986
I'd like your help.

32:34.020 --> 32:37.623
I take it I'm not
gonna get it.

32:37.656 --> 32:39.758
Okay.

32:39.791 --> 32:40.659
[ Door opens ]

32:40.692 --> 32:42.628
Wait.

32:42.661 --> 32:44.430
What's the story
with this kid?

32:44.463 --> 32:46.632
Why is it
so important to you?

32:46.665 --> 32:48.367
[ Sighs ]

32:48.400 --> 32:49.501
Why not?

32:49.535 --> 32:52.671
Because letting things
get personal is a sure formula

32:52.704 --> 32:55.774
for screwing things up.

32:55.807 --> 32:57.143
I don't know.

32:57.176 --> 33:00.279
Letting things get
personal is how we...

33:00.312 --> 33:03.415
[sighs]...how we
make it matter.

33:06.252 --> 33:08.287
[ Sighs ]

33:11.557 --> 33:15.294
So, are you proud
or disappointed?

33:15.327 --> 33:17.663
Do I have
to pick just one?

33:17.696 --> 33:24.570
**

33:24.603 --> 33:28.574
Hey.

33:28.607 --> 33:30.542
You're new
to town, right?

33:30.576 --> 33:32.211
Yes.

33:32.244 --> 33:34.346
Well, I'm sure you have
a lot of questions.

33:34.380 --> 33:36.348
No.

33:36.382 --> 33:38.617
Uh...

33:38.650 --> 33:42.221
You got to be curious about
the place, about the people.

33:42.254 --> 33:44.656
Dr. Glassman gave me
a map of the hospital,

33:44.690 --> 33:47.759
and I got a map
of San Jose online.

33:49.861 --> 33:52.464
[ Chuckles ] Okay.

33:52.498 --> 33:55.267
Great.

33:58.704 --> 34:00.572
I do have one question.

34:00.606 --> 34:04.076
Yeah?

34:04.110 --> 34:06.412
Why were you rude to me
when we first met,

34:06.445 --> 34:08.414
then nicer to me
the second time we met,

34:08.447 --> 34:11.117
and now you want
to be my friend?

34:11.150 --> 34:14.553
Which time was it
that you were pretending?

34:17.356 --> 34:20.859
Shaun. We're ready.

34:20.892 --> 34:27.499
**

34:27.533 --> 34:30.569
The vote was clear.
Why are we reopening this?

34:30.602 --> 34:32.471
Is it really because
of a piece of publicity?

34:32.504 --> 34:34.606
It's because the man just
saved somebody's life.

34:34.640 --> 34:35.707
And thank God for that,

34:35.741 --> 34:37.443
but it doesn't change
a single thing we discussed.

34:37.476 --> 34:38.744
Glassman:
Give him six months.

34:38.777 --> 34:42.348
If he proves anything
less than excellent --

34:42.381 --> 34:44.750
Someone "less than excellent"
means someone else dies.

34:44.783 --> 34:47.786
Well, I-I would love
to make you happy, Doctor.

34:47.819 --> 34:50.756
I would love to hire someone
who never, ever makes a mistake.

34:50.789 --> 34:53.692
Unfortunately,
God already has a job.

34:53.725 --> 34:56.195
I can accept that
he will have insights

34:56.228 --> 34:58.264
that none of the rest
of us will have.

34:58.297 --> 34:59.831
Can you accept that
he will make mistakes

34:59.865 --> 35:01.167
none of the rest of us
will make?

35:01.200 --> 35:04.203
You won't be the one
who pays the price.

35:08.740 --> 35:13.312
If Shaun doesn't live up to
everything I know he can do,

35:13.345 --> 35:15.647
he will be
immediately released.

35:15.681 --> 35:20.319
And I will resign my position
as President of this hospital.

35:22.654 --> 35:25.324
We haven't heard
from Dr. Murphy yet.

35:25.357 --> 35:30.662
Perhaps we should hear from him
before we decide his fate.

35:30.696 --> 35:33.699
Shaun...

35:48.414 --> 35:51.283
Dr. Murphy...

35:51.317 --> 35:55.254
I'd like you to tell us why
you want to become a surgeon.

36:10.502 --> 36:13.372
**

36:13.405 --> 36:15.474
Why do I want them
to be my friends?

36:15.507 --> 36:17.443
Everybody needs friends,
Shaun.

36:17.476 --> 36:20.846
It's gonna be cool, okay?
Play hide and seek maybe?

36:20.879 --> 36:23.349
Okay.
Tag in the warehouse?

36:23.382 --> 36:28.754
**

36:28.787 --> 36:31.323
Hey,
stop following me.

36:31.357 --> 36:41.333
**

36:41.367 --> 36:51.310
**

36:51.343 --> 37:01.387
**

37:01.420 --> 37:03.822
**

37:03.855 --> 37:04.956
Told ya it was fun, right?

37:04.990 --> 37:06.692
Shh!

37:06.725 --> 37:12.698
**

37:12.731 --> 37:14.466
Hey, you know what?

37:14.500 --> 37:18.804
[ Gasps, screams ]

37:18.837 --> 37:21.607
[ Thud ]

37:21.640 --> 37:31.617
**

37:31.650 --> 37:41.627
**

37:51.637 --> 37:56.342
The day that the rain
smelled like ice cream,

37:56.375 --> 38:04.783
my bunny went to heaven
in front of my eyes.

38:04.816 --> 38:08.019
The day that the copper pipes
in the old building smelled like

38:08.053 --> 38:15.361
burnt food, my brother...

38:15.394 --> 38:18.930
went to heaven
in front of my eyes.

38:21.933 --> 38:24.803
I couldn't save them.

38:24.836 --> 38:28.940
It's sad.

38:28.974 --> 38:33.879
Neither one had the chance
to become an adult.

38:33.912 --> 38:39.718
They should have become adults.

38:39.751 --> 38:42.788
They should have had
children of their own

38:42.821 --> 38:46.958
and loved those children.

38:50.962 --> 38:53.665
And I want
to make that possible

38:53.699 --> 38:56.868
for other people.

38:56.902 --> 39:06.111
**

39:06.144 --> 39:08.146
And I want to make
a lot of money

39:08.179 --> 39:12.718
so that I can have a television.

39:12.751 --> 39:21.593
**

39:21.627 --> 39:26.832
Dr. Murphy...

39:26.865 --> 39:30.001
I want to be the first
to welcome you

39:30.035 --> 39:33.405
to San Jose
St. Bonaventure Hospital.

39:33.439 --> 39:36.074
**

39:36.107 --> 39:38.477
We're very proud to have you.

39:38.510 --> 39:42.147
[ Applause ]

39:42.180 --> 39:48.186
**

39:48.219 --> 39:53.759
Shaun, Dr. Melendez's
team is going into surgery.

39:53.792 --> 39:56.628
I mean,
if you're interested.

40:01.467 --> 40:10.809
**

40:10.842 --> 40:20.151
**

40:20.185 --> 40:29.695
**

40:29.728 --> 40:39.070
**

40:39.104 --> 40:48.647
**

40:48.680 --> 40:57.989
**

40:58.023 --> 41:01.092
Got a messy
field here.

41:01.126 --> 41:03.529
Murphy.

41:03.562 --> 41:10.902
**

41:10.936 --> 41:13.639
Shaun: Suction.

41:13.672 --> 41:19.110
**

41:19.144 --> 41:22.047
Never forget,
you're the smart one.

41:22.080 --> 41:24.182
You can do anything.

41:24.215 --> 41:27.586
And I'm proud
of you, Shaun.

41:27.619 --> 41:33.525
**

41:33.559 --> 41:35.561
Bet you've seen
many of these.

41:38.129 --> 41:40.699
I remember my first.

41:40.732 --> 41:44.970
Kept thinking, "It doesn't get
any better than this."

41:45.003 --> 41:48.574
And for you, I'm afraid,
that's literally true.

41:50.809 --> 41:54.580
You're a nice kid,
and you're obviously very smart,

41:54.613 --> 41:57.683
but you don't belong here.

41:57.716 --> 41:59.651
So, as long as you're
part of my team,

41:59.685 --> 42:03.922
this is all you're ever
going to be doing -- suction.

42:07.726 --> 42:12.197
I saw a lot of surgeons
in medical school.

42:12.230 --> 42:14.199
You're much better
than them.

42:14.232 --> 42:16.768
I have a lot
to learn from you.

42:16.802 --> 42:23.041
**

42:23.074 --> 42:26.244
You're very arrogant.

42:26.277 --> 42:30.281
Do you think that helps you
be a good surgeon?

42:30.315 --> 42:34.219
Does it hurt you
as a person?

42:34.252 --> 42:36.922
Is it worth it?

42:36.955 --> 42:43.128
**

42:47.999 --> 42:57.308
**

42:57.342 --> 43:06.918
**

43:06.952 --> 43:16.294
**
